    "narrative": "For LawDog\u2019s April 17th slate, the highest ceiling belongs to **Lawrence Butler** (74.61), who benefits from a massive park and platoon advantage against Martin. While his position at the bottom of the order drags his score slightly, the favorable matchup against a 4.68 xERA arm makes him an elite play. **Will Smith** (72.25) follows closely, buoyed by a favorable matchup against Sugano and the stability of the #3 spot. We also see high-efficiency output from our core anchors: **Luis Arraez** (68.47), **Matt Chapman** (67.92), and **Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00edrez** (65.30), all of whom are set to capitalize on favorable RHP matchups. The primary concern today is the start for **Cal Raleigh** (46.16), who draws an elite matchup against deGrom; he remains in the lineup only due to positional scarcity, as his raw metrics are heavily suppressed by the SP\u2019s high-tier skill.\n\nThe most difficult bench decision was opting to sit **Drew Gilbert** (51.68) over **Gavin Sheets** (51.29). Despite **Gilbert** holding a slightly higher raw score, the volatility of the #9 spot combined with team-wide rotation requirements for game cap management led to the decision to bench him. Our strategy today hinges on the platoon edges enjoyed by **Gleyber Torres** (+13% vs. LHP) and **Jung Hoo Lee** (+10% vs. RHP), as both look to maximize their efficiency against Suarez and Littell respectively. We are also monitoring the risk associated with **Wenceel Perez** (53.30); while he benefits from the platoon split, his status as an \"Elite Hold\" player in the SB category forces us to accept lower raw point totals to prioritize his speed contribution to our 5x5 totals. Tread carefully with **Raleigh** against the elite arm, but rely on the middle-infield production from **Arraez** and **Torres** to stabilize the offensive floor.",
